d Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Longueval was born in 1225, his father, Aubert Ier “le Chien” de Longueval, was 36 and his mother, Blanche d'Acheux-en-Amiénois, was 21. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Catherine de Châtillon-Saint-Pol. He died in 1273, in Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1225–1273":"1225–1273","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1225–1265":"1225–1265","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1257–1295":"1257–1295","1260–1308":"1260–1308","1190–1262":"1190–1262","1205–1284":"1205–1284","1190":"1190","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","1273":"1273","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","ABT 1260":"umbes 1260","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","1257":"1257","1235":"1235","1265":"1265","1308":"1308","Sieur, de Longueval, Ch‚telain, de PÈronne":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Frankreich":"Prantsusmaa","Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France":"Longueval, Som